POP Design Rationale
Introduction
Software development consists of two activities: forming intent and communicating it.
We decide what a system should do, then we describe that decision in a form a computer can execute. The first activity is a practice of intentionality. The second is a practice of communication.
Historically, these concerns have been fused together into source code. This has worked remarkably well. Source code is one of the most successful communication systems ever created, allowing humans and computers to collaborate through a shared artifact.
Yet source code is ultimately an implementation. Technical details are required for software to function. Readable intent is not.
As software evolves, this distinction becomes increasingly important. Requirements change, teams grow, systems become more complex, and new contributors must understand decisions they did not make. The implementation remains available, but the reasoning behind it gradually becomes harder to access. We return to the code and attempt to modify it without violating the ideas that originally justified its existence.
This is difficult because intent is a nicer material to work with than implementation. It is easier to understand, easier to discuss, easier to review, easier to expand, and easier to change. For decades, software engineering has recognized the value of separating intent from implementation. The challenge has always been keeping the two synchronized.
What is new is our ability to translate between them automatically.
AI systems are capable of producing implementation from intent while preserving important constraints. This creates a new possibility: intent can become a first-class software artifact.
POP is a language built around this idea.
Intent is written directly as code.
Implementation is derived from it.
POP aims to keep developers working at the layer of intent while driving implementation details into the compiler. Its purpose is to minimize the gap between what the programmer means and what the compiler builds.

───

Intent-Oriented Programming
The philosophy behind POP can be described as Intent-Oriented Programming.
Traditional software development stores intent and implementation together. This is often convenient while software is being written because the author understands both the implementation and the reasoning behind it. The challenge appears later. Software must be reviewed, modified, extended, maintained, and increasingly generated by automated systems. At that point, implementation remains directly available while intent must often be reconstructed.
Software projects attempt to preserve intent through comments, documentation, tests, design documents, tickets, and institutional knowledge. These artifacts are valuable, but they remain secondary to the language itself.
POP takes a different approach. Intent is expressed directly in the language and implementation is derived from it. Instead of complaining about syntax, the compiler should complain about missing ideas or unclear meaning.
Changes are made at the intent layer rather than the implementation layer. Generated code can increasingly be treated as a disposable artifact. The specification becomes the authoritative representation of the system.

───

Intent Alignment
The central challenge of Intent-Oriented Programming is alignment.
How can a compiler know whether it has correctly understood what the programmer intended?
Many AI systems respond to ambiguity by making reasonable assumptions and continuing. This is often useful, but it can also create a growing gap between the system the programmer intended to build and the system that is ultimately generated.
POP addresses this problem through intent alignment.
Intent alignment is the process of reducing the gap between what the programmer means and what the compiler builds. Rather than attempting to eliminate interpretation, POP makes interpretation visible and manageable.
The compiler is expected to participate in the alignment process by identifying ambiguity, missing requirements, contradictory specifications, and unstable descriptions. The goal is not merely to generate code. The goal is to generate code that accurately reflects programmer intent.
POP treats software generation as a collaborative activity between programmer and compiler. The programmer provides intent. The compiler provides implementation, feedback, and clarification. Together they refine a specification until both share a sufficiently aligned understanding of the system being built.

───

Stability
Not all specifications constrain a compiler equally.
Consider the specification:
text
[function Whatever]

Do something.

This specification provides almost no guidance. The programmer has delegated nearly all implementation decisions to the compiler.
Now consider:
text
[function Sort Users]

Sort users by account creation date in ascending order.

This specification constrains the compiler much more tightly. The programmer has retained greater control over the resulting implementation.
POP refers to this property as stability.
An idea is stable when different people understand it the same way. A specification is stable when different implementations preserve the same meaning.
Stability measures how much implementation freedom remains within a specification. High-stability specifications tightly constrain the compiler. Low-stability specifications delegate more decisions to it. Specifications with no stability may leave nearly all meaningful decisions unspecified.
This does not make low-stability specifications inherently wrong. Delegation is one of the primary benefits of AI-assisted development. Stability exists so that delegation becomes a conscious choice rather than an invisible risk.
Without stability, interpretation is hidden. With stability, interpretation becomes observable.

───

Findings
Traditional compilers primarily report violations of formal rules. POP compilers perform a broader role.
A POP compiler is expected to help refine the specification itself.
When a compiler encounters ambiguity, instability, contradictions, missing requirements, or other concerns, it produces findings. Findings are not merely error messages. They are part of the authoring process.
Most AI systems are optimized to produce answers. POP encourages compilers to also identify uncertainty. Sometimes the correct response to a specification is not an implementation but a question.
Instead of complaining about syntax, the compiler should complain about missing ideas or unclear meaning.
This creates a different relationship between programmer and compiler. The compiler is not merely a translator. It is an active participant in refining intent.

───

Findings and Policy
Different teams have different tolerances for ambiguity, delegation, and risk.
For this reason, POP separates findings from policy.
A finding is an observation about a specification. A policy determines how that observation should affect compilation.
One organization may reject unstable specifications. Another may merely warn about them. A third may actively encourage experimentation and delegation.
The same specification may therefore be accepted in one environment and rejected in another.
This separation allows organizations to define their own standards without changing the language itself.


Complete Units of Intent

One of the lessons that shaped POP emerged from practical experience with AI-assisted software generation.

Modern AI systems are remarkably good at creating complete implementations from clear specifications. They are significantly less effective when asked to perform large numbers of incremental modifications to partially understood systems. The further a system drifts from its original intent, the more difficult it becomes to reason about the consequences of change.

This observation influenced the structure of POP itself.

Functions, Types, Imports, Modifiers, and Actions are intended to represent complete units of intent rather than partial modifications. A POP document describes what exists within a system rather than how an existing implementation should be edited.

This is not merely a convenience for the compiler. Humans also reason more effectively about complete things. We understand a user, a registration flow, a validation rule, or a payment processor more easily than we understand a sequence of disconnected edits applied across a large codebase.

By organizing software around complete units of intent, POP encourages specifications that are easier to understand, easier to review, and easier to generate.

───

Modifiers and Context

Many software requirements are not local.

Validation policies, architectural constraints, deployment assumptions, coding conventions, asynchronous behavior, framework requirements, security standards, and organizational practices often apply across an entire document or subsystem rather than to a single function.

Expressing these assumptions repeatedly quickly becomes verbose and difficult to maintain. More importantly, repetition obscures the distinction between what a system does and the context in which it operates.

Modifiers exist to solve this problem.

From a technical perspective, modifiers provide document-wide constraints. From a conceptual perspective, they define the context in which a document should be understood.

This distinction is important.

A function should primarily describe behavior. A type should primarily describe structure. Context belongs elsewhere.

Modifiers allow programmers to establish assumptions once and rely on them throughout the specification. This reduces repetition while preserving clarity.

The role of modifiers is intentionally broad. Context itself is broad. As POP evolves, modifiers may become one of the most expressive mechanisms available to programmers because they allow intent to be communicated at a level above individual entities.

───

AI-Assisted Development

POP is not intended to replace AI-assisted software development.

In many ways, POP assumes its existence.

AI systems may generate POP documents. They may refine POP documents. They may compile POP documents into code. The language does not prescribe a particular workflow and does not require a particular generation technology.

The distinction is that POP attempts to keep software development at the intent layer.

Many AI-assisted workflows begin with intent, generate implementation, and then perform future changes by analyzing and modifying that generated implementation. As a result, both humans and machines are repeatedly forced to reconstruct intent from code.

POP seeks to avoid this cycle.

Instead of treating generated code as the primary artifact, POP treats the specification as the authoritative representation of the system. Changes are applied to the specification. Implementations are regenerated from it.

This reduces the need for reverse engineering and helps preserve the original goals, constraints, and structure of a system as it evolves.

The objective is not to eliminate implementation. Software ultimately exists to run.

The objective is to ensure that implementation remains derived from intent rather than becoming a substitute for it.

───

Human Readability

POP is often described as a language for AI-assisted software generation. While true, this description is incomplete.

POP is equally a language for humans.

A specification is expected to be read, reviewed, discussed, modified, challenged, and improved by people. The fact that a compiler can understand it is important. The fact that another programmer can understand it is essential.

This is one of the reasons POP favors explicit structure. Explicit names, explicit entity kinds, explicit relationships, and explicit constraints all improve the ability of humans to reason about a system.

A programmer can still write vague, unstable, or poorly organized specifications. POP does not guarantee maintainability.

What POP provides is a language in which maintainability, clarity, and structure can be expressed directly. The language makes these qualities possible. The programmer remains responsible for achieving them.

Because intent is written directly as code, many existing software engineering practices become applicable at the specification level. Specifications can be version controlled, reviewed, discussed, compared across revisions, generated automatically, analyzed, and refined.

These are not special POP features. They are natural consequences of treating intent as a first-class software artifact.

───

Beyond Code Generation

It is tempting to view POP primarily as a tool for generating code.

That perspective is useful, but incomplete.

The deeper purpose of POP is to create a shared representation of software intent.

Code generation is one application of that representation. Review, collaboration, architecture discussion, system design, onboarding, maintenance, and automated analysis are others.

The value of a POP specification does not come solely from the code it produces. Its value comes from making the reasoning behind a system explicit and preserving that reasoning as the system evolves.

In this sense, POP should not be understood as an alternative programming language competing with existing languages. It occupies a different layer.

Programming languages describe implementation.

POP describes intent.

The two are complementary.

───

Conclusion

The desire to separate intent from implementation is not new. Software engineering has been exploring different ways to preserve intent for decades through documentation, specifications, models, conventions, and design processes.

The difficulty has always been synchronization. Intent and implementation inevitably drift apart when they are maintained independently.

POP becomes practical because implementation can now be derived from intent automatically.

This changes the relationship between programmer, compiler, and code.

The programmer is no longer responsible for expressing every implementation detail. The compiler is no longer limited to validating syntax. Generated code is no longer the authoritative representation of a system.

Intent becomes the primary artifact.

Software becomes a collaboration between the programmer and their compiler.

By separating intent from implementation, introducing mechanisms for intent alignment, exposing stability as a measurable property, and encouraging specifications built from complete units of intent, POP seeks to minimize the gap between what the programmer means and what the compiler builds.

Intent is written directly as code.

Implementation is derived from it.
